'''Aimee Lou Wood ''' (born 3 February 1994)<ref>{{Cite web |last=McLean |first=Craig |date=17 February 2025 |title=In The White Lotus, Aimee Lou Wood is acting like herself |url=https://theface.com/culture/white-lotus-season-three-aimee-lou-wood-interview |url-status=live |access-date=26 February 2025 |website=[[The Face]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Tate |first=Gabriel |date=25 February 2025 |title=Aimee Lou Wood says Netflix's Toxic Town reveals an uncomfortable truth |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/tv/drama/aimee-lou-wood-toxic-town/ |url-status=live |access-date=26 February 2025 |website=[[Radio Times]]}}</ref> is an English actress. After early stage roles in ''[[Mary Stuart (Schiller play)|Mary Stuart]]'' (2016–2017) and ''[[People, Places and Things]]'' (2017), Wood made her screen debut on the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Sex Education (TV series)|Sex Education]]'' (2019–2023), which won her a [[British Academy Television Awards|British Academy Television Award]] for [[British Academy Television Award for Best Female Comedy Performance|Best Female Comedy Performance]].

Wood subsequently had roles in the films ''[[The Electrical Life of Louis Wain]]'' (2021) and ''[[Living (2022 film)|Living]]'' (2022), the [[BBC Three]] comedy series ''[[Daddy Issues (TV series)|Daddy Issues]]'' (2024), as well as stage productions of ''[[Uncle Vanya]]'' in 2020 and ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]'' in 2023. She has since starred in the third season of the [[HBO]] anthology series ''[[The White Lotus]]'' (2025).

==Early life and education ==
Aimee Lou Wood was born in 1994 in [[Stockport]], [[Greater Manchester]], and grew up in the upmarket Greater Manchester suburb of [[Bramhall]].<ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://www.wonderlandmagazine.com/2020/04/16/aimee-lou-wood-rollacoaster-ss20/|title=Meet Sex Education break out star Aimee Lou Wood|journal=Wonderland|first=Erin|last=Cobby|date=16 April 2020|accessdate=19 October 2023}}</ref> Her mother works for [[Childline]] and her father is a car dealer.<ref name="stand">{{Cite web|last=Dex|first=Robert|date=2020-01-24|title= Aimee Lou Wood on a badly timed press night text message from her dad|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/culture/theatre/aimee-lou-wood-uncle-vanya-interview-a4343371.html|access-date=2021-06-09|website=www.standard.co.uk|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wiseman |first=Eva |date=2023-02-12 |title=Aimee Lou Wood: 'I am a wrecking ball of emotion' |language=en-GB |work=The Observer |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2023/feb/12/aimee-lou-wood-interview-sex-education-actor-cabaret |access-date=2023-05-05 |issn=0029-7712}}</ref> Her sister Emily Wood is a makeup artist.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://notion.online/aimee-and-emily-wood/|title=Aimee and Emily Wood|journal=Notion|first=Cal|last=MacIntyre|date=28 June 2019|accessdate=19 October 2023}}</ref>

Following their parents' divorce, Wood attended [[Cheadle Hulme School]].<ref name="chead">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cheadlehulmeschool.co.uk/chs-life/news/old-waconians-stage-screen-and-director%E2%80%99s-chair |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210128103442/https://www.cheadlehulmeschool.co.uk/chs-life/news/old-waconians-stage-screen-and-director%E2%80%99s-chair |archive-date=2021-01-28  |title=Old Waconians on the stage, screen and in the director's chair|website=Cheadle Hulme School|accessdate=21 January 2021}}</ref>  She then took a foundation course at the [[Oxford School of Drama]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oxforddrama.ac.uk/downloads/FINAL-Prospectus-20-21.pdf|title=Oxford School of Drama Prospectus |date=2020 |website= Oxford School of Drama |url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129202242/https://www.oxforddrama.ac.uk/downloads/FINAL-Prospectus-20-21.pdf|archive-date=29 January 2020|access-date=}}</ref> and went on to graduate with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in Acting from the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] (RADA) in 2017.<ref name="yahoo">{{cite web | last=Bergado | first=Gabe | title= Sex Education Star Aimee Lou Wood on the Power of Female Pleasure, Her Love for RuPaul's Drag Race, and the Iconic "My Ham!" Line | url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/em-sex-education-em-star-093000663.html?guccounter=1 |website= yahoo.com |date=25 January 2019 }}</ref>

She has mostly retained her [[Social class in the United Kingdom#Accent and language and social class| accent]].<ref name="bu
